## Slide 4 — The Alice–Bob–Eve Framework
**Title:** Three Agents, One Game

**Visual — horizontal flow diagram:**
```
┌─────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌─────────┐
│  Alice  │────▶│ Cipher C │────▶│   Bob   │───▶ P̂_B ✅
└─────────┘     └──────────┘     └─────────┘
     │                │
     ▼                ▼
  Secret Key K    ┌─────────┐
     │            │   Eve   │───▶ P̂_E ❌
     └───────────▶└─────────┘
```
*Eve only sees ciphertext C — no key access*

**Three info cards:**

| Agent | Role | Input | Has Key? | Objective |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Alice** | Sender/Encoder | Plaintext P + Key K | ✅ | Encrypt so Bob can decode but Eve cannot |
| **Bob** | Receiver/Decoder | Ciphertext C + Key K | ✅ | Reconstruct P perfectly |
| **Eve** | Eavesdropper/Attacker | Ciphertext C only | ❌ | Reconstruct P from C alone |

**Key insight:** Eve is **structurally disadvantaged** — same architecture, half the input information. This asymmetry is the source of security.

