## Slide 5 — The Adversarial Objective
**Title:** Training as a Minimax Game

**Two columns:**

Left — **Alice & Bob's Goal:**
- Bob must reconstruct P accurately
- Eve must be **indistinguishable from random guessing**
- Random baseline for N-bit message = N/2 bits wrong
- Loss combines both objectives:

$$L_{AB} = \underbrace{\frac{1}{B}\sum\frac{d_1(P,\hat{P}_B)}{N}}_{\text{Bob's reconstruction}} + \underbrace{\mathcal{L}_{\text{adv}}(P,\hat{P}_E)}_{\text{Adversarial penalty}}$$

Right — **Eve's Goal:**
- Minimise her own reconstruction error
- Trained **independently** with separate optimizer
- Gets more training steps per round (configurable)

$$L_E = \frac{1}{B}\sum d_1(P,\hat{P}_E)$$

**Bottom box — The Quadratic Adversarial Penalty (original paper):**
$$\mathcal{L}_{\text{adv}} = \frac{\left(\frac{N}{2} - d_1(P,\hat{P}_E)\right)^2}{\left(\frac{N}{2}\right)^2}$$

*Minimized when Eve's error = N/2 — the sweet spot between too good and trivially reversible*

