## Slide 8 — Why {-1,+1} Instead of {0,1}?
**Title:** The Importance of Representation

**Two columns:**

Left — **Binary choice matters:**
- XOR in {0,1}: $a \oplus b = a + b \mod 2$ — not differentiable
- XOR in {-1,+1}: $a \oplus b = a \times b$ — smooth and differentiable
- Gradient descent needs smooth functions to learn

Right — **Ciphertext is continuous:**
- Alice's output is floating-point in [-1,+1]
- Tanh activation enforces this range
- Allows gradient to flow through ciphertext back to Alice
- Bob and Eve must learn to interpret continuous values

**Bottom formula:**
$$C_i \in (-1,+1),\quad \hat{P}_{B,i} \in (-1,+1),\quad \hat{P}_{E,i} \in (-1,+1)$$

**Quote:** *"If we forced binary outputs, gradients would vanish and learning would be impossible."*

