## Slide 12 — Why NOT Contrastive Learning?
**Title:** Could We Just Use Contrastive Learning?

**Two-column deep dive:**

| **Contrastive Learning** | **Adversarial Neural Crypto** |
|---|---|
| Pulls **similar samples** together in embedding space | Three **competing agents** with conflicting objectives |
| Pushes **dissimilar samples** apart | Goal: learn to **encrypt and decrypt** |
| Goal: learn good **representations** | No dataset — randomly generated data |
| Needs a dataset (images, text, etc.) | Multi-agent adversarial game |
| One model, no competition | Signal comes from agent competition |
| Examples: SimCLR, CLIP, MoCo, BYOL | Not sample similarity |

**Why it fundamentally can't work:**

❌ **No notion of "similar" ciphertexts** — what would that even mean?

❌ **Security requires a live adversary** — not a fixed distance metric

❌ **Contrastive learning produces embeddings** — not encryption/decryption functions

❌ **Eve needs to actively attack** — not just be a "negative sample"

**Bottom line:** Both involve opposing forces, but they operate in completely different spaces — contrastive learning pushes **data points** apart, neural crypto pushes **agents** apart.

