## Slide 16 — ASCII Text Mode: Human-Readable Encryption
**Title:** From Random Bits to Real Text

**Two columns:**

Left — **How it works:**
- 16 bits = 2 characters per block
- Printable ASCII codes 32-126
- Bitwise encoding preserves {-1,+1} domain
- Long messages chunked into blocks (like ECB mode)

**Encoding example:**
```
"He" → [H=72, e=101] → bits → {-1,+1}^16
```

Right — **Results (seed 13):**

| Metric | ASCII | Random |
|---|---|---|
| Bob error | 0.04 bits | 0.56 bits |
| Eve error | 7.32 bits | 7.62 bits |
| Robustness | 6.20 bits | 9.04 bits |
| Secure runs | 2/5 | 5/5 |

**The catch:** ASCII has **structural bias** — printable chars have MSB = 0 always. Eve gets **one free bit per block** without any cryptanalysis.

**Demo output:**
