## Slide 17 — Security Analysis: How Secure Is It REALLY?
**Title:** Empirical Robustness ≠ Provable Security

**Three columns with clear distinctions:**

| ❌ **Not IND-CPA** | ❌ **Not Perfect Secrecy** | ✅ **Empirically Robust** |
|---|---|---|
| No proof against all polynomial-time adversaries | Requires key length ≥ message length | Fresh Eve retrained from scratch can't break it |
| Only tested against neural net attackers | Key is only 16 bits (tiny!) | 5/5 secure runs in baseline |
| Attackers use same architecture | Plaintext distribution not uniform | Mean 9.04 bits (113% of baseline) |
| Bounded training budget (5k steps) | | Survives multiple independent attacks |

**The Security Gap:**
```
Provable Security (IND-CPA) ←――[GAP]――→ Empirical Robustness
     (What we WANT)                        (What we HAVE)
```

**What the gap means:**
- A more powerful attacker (transformer, non-neural, more steps) might break it
- No mathematical proof — only experimental evidence
- This is the **central open problem** in the field

**Bottom line:** Neural crypto is a **proof of concept**, not a replacement for AES.

